Dutch politicians and commentators were united in their condemnation of the murder, in broad daylight on an Amsterdam street, of controversial filmmaker Theo van Gogh and called for calm together with representatives of the Dutch Muslim community.
Many immediately drew parallels between the murder of Van Gogh, was shot and stabbed to death while cycling on an Amsterdam street, and the assassination of outspoken politician Pim Fortuyn on May 6, 2002.
Muslims, in turn, say new anti-immigration and anti-terrorism laws unfairly discriminate against them.
The Dutch police authorities have arrested eight suspects concerning the killing of the famous film maker
